Radio-frequency electrical currents are usually carried by specially-designed [transmission line](/Transmission_line) such as [coaxial cable](/Coaxial_cable), as ordinary [electrical cables](/Electrical_cable) would have high power loss.

Radio frequency (RF) refers to the [oscillation](/Oscillation) rate of an [alternating electric current](/Alternating_current), [voltage](/Voltage), or a [magnetic](/Magnetic_field), electric, or [electromagnetic field](/Electromagnetic_field), or even a mechanical system, within a specific frequency range. This range typically spans from approximately 20 [kHz](/Kilohertz) up to about 300 [GHz](/Gigahertz). To put that into perspective, it’s the spectrum nestled between the highest frequencies humans can audibly perceive (though those are not electromagnetic in nature) and the lower threshold of [infrared](/Infrared) light. It also conveniently encompasses the entire [microwave](/Microwave) band. The significance of this particular frequency range lies in its ability to efficiently radiate energy from an oscillating current in a conductor out into space, manifesting as [radio waves](/Radio_wave). This fundamental property is the bedrock of all [radio](/Radio) technology and a myriad of other applications. It’s worth noting that the precise boundaries of what constitutes “radio frequency” can vary slightly depending on the source and context, a minor quibble in the grand scheme of things.

### Electric Current

Boy allowing the arc from a [Tesla coil](/Tesla_coil) to strike his hand. Coming in contact with radio frequency arcs as shown here is extremely dangerous and can result in electrocution.

[Electric currents](/Electric_current) that oscillate at radio frequencies, often termed RF currents, exhibit peculiar behaviors that set them apart from their direct current (DC) or lower-frequency alternating current (AC) counterparts, such as the ubiquitous 50 or 60 Hz currents powering our homes and cities via [electrical power distribution](/Electrical_power_distribution).

*   **Radiant Energy:** A key characteristic is the capacity for energy to detach itself from the conductor and propagate through space as [electromagnetic waves](/Electromagnetic_wave), specifically [radio waves](/Radio_wave). This phenomenon is the very essence of [radio](/Radio) communication.
*   **Skin Effect:** RF currents possess a pronounced tendency to congregate and flow along the *surface* of electrical conductors, rather than penetrating deeply within. This is the well-documented [skin effect](/Skin_effect).
*   **Physiological Impact:** Unlike their lower-frequency brethren, RF currents often fail to elicit the familiar, painful sensation of [electric shock](/Electric_shock) or the involuntary muscular contractions it triggers. The reason for this is the sheer speed at which the current reverses direction, far too rapid to stimulate the [depolarization](/Depolarization) necessary for nerve signal transmission. However, this absence of immediate shock does not equate to harmlessness. RF currents can inflict internal damage and cause severe superficial burns, often referred to as [RF burns](/Radiation_burn).
*   **Ionization Potential:** RF currents possess the ability to [ionize](/Ionize) air, effectively creating a conductive pathway through it. This property is ingeniously harnessed in high-frequency units employed in electric [arc welding](/Arc_welding), which utilize currents oscillating at frequencies significantly higher than those found in standard power distribution.
*   **Capacitive Behavior:** Another intriguing characteristic is the apparent ability of RF currents to traverse paths that include insulating materials, such as the [dielectric](/Dielectric) insulator within a [capacitor](/Capacitor). This is a direct consequence of [capacitive reactance](/Capacitive_reactance) diminishing as frequency increases within a circuit.
*   **Inductive Opposition:** Conversely, a coil of wire, or even a simple bend or turn within a wire, can effectively impede or block RF current. This is due to the [inductive reactance](/Inductive_reactance) of a circuit escalating with rising frequency.
*   **Wave Reflections:** When RF current is confined within an ordinary electric cable, it tends to bounce back from any discontinuities, like connectors, and travel toward the source. This creates a phenomenon known as [standing waves](/Standing_wave). To mitigate this, RF currents are more efficiently managed and transmitted over specialized [transmission lines](/Transmission_line), such as [coaxial cables](/Coaxial_cable).

### Frequency Bands

The vast expanse of the [radio spectrum](/Radio_spectrum) is systematically partitioned into distinct bands, each bearing conventional names and designations established by the [International Telecommunication Union](/International_Telecommunication_Union) (ITU). These designations provide a standardized framework for allocating and managing these crucial frequencies.

| Frequency Range | Wavelength Range | ITU Designation | IEEE Bands | Full Name | Abbreviation |
| :-------------- | :--------------- | :-------------- | :--------- | :-------- | :----------- |
| Below 3 Hz | >10⁵ km | — | — | — | — |
| 3–30 Hz | 10⁵–10⁴ km | [Extremely low frequency](/Extremely_low_frequency) | [ELF](/Extremely_low_frequency) | — | — |
| 30–300 Hz | 10⁴–10³ km | [Super low frequency](/Super_low_frequency) | [SLF](/Super_low_frequency) | — | — |
| 300–3000 Hz | 10³–100 km | [Ultra low frequency](/Ultra_low_frequency) | [ULF](/Ultra_low_frequency) | — | — |
| 3–30 kHz | 100–10 km | [Very low frequency](/Very_low_frequency) | [VLF](/VLF) | — | — |
| 30–300 kHz | 10–1 km | [Low frequency](/Low_frequency) | [LF](/Low_frequency) | — | — |
| 300 kHz – 3 MHz | 1 km – 100 m | [Medium frequency](/Medium_frequency) | [MF](/Medium_frequency) | — | — |
| 3–30 MHz | 100–10 m | [High frequency](/High_frequency) | [HF](/High_frequency) | [HF](/High_frequency) | [HF](/High_frequency) |
| 30–300 MHz | 10–1 m | [Very high frequency](/Very_high_frequency) | [VHF](/VHF) | [VHF](/VHF) | [VHF](/VHF) |
| 300 MHz – 3 GHz | 1 m – 100 mm | [Ultra high frequency](/Ultra_high_frequency) | [UHF](/UHF), [L](/L_band), [S](/S_band) | [Ultra high frequency](/Ultra_high_frequency) | [UHF](/UHF) |
| 3–30 GHz | 100–10 mm | [Super high frequency](/Super_high_frequency) | [S](/S_band), [C](/C_band_(IEEE)), [X](/X_band), [Ku](/Ku_band), [K](/K_band_(IEEE)), [Ka](/Ka_band) | [Super high frequency](/Super_high_frequency) | [SHF](/Super_high_frequency) |
| 30–300 GHz | 10–1 mm | [Extremely high frequency](/Extremely_high_frequency) | [Ka](/Ka_band), [V](/V_band), [W](/W_band), [mm](/Millimetre_band) | [Extremely high frequency](/Extremely_high_frequency) | [EHF](/Extremely_high_frequency) |
