The convention dictates that frequencies at or above 1 [GHz](/Gigahertz) are generally categorized as [microwaves](/Microwave), while those starting at 30 [GHz](/Gigahertz) and extending upward are referred to as [millimeter waves](/Millimeter_wave). Beyond these ITU designations, more granular classifications exist, such as the [IEEE](/IEEE) letter-band frequency designations and the EU/NATO designations, providing further detail for specific applications and engineering contexts.

### Applications

The utility of radio frequencies is vast and touches nearly every facet of modern life. Its applications span from the ubiquitous broadcasting of entertainment and news, through essential voice and data communication systems, to sophisticated technologies like radar for detection and navigation, precise radiolocation, and even vital medical treatments and remote control systems.

### Measurement

The apparatus required for measuring radio frequencies varies significantly with the frequency itself. At the lower end of the RF spectrum, standard laboratory instruments may suffice. However, as frequencies climb, the test equipment becomes increasingly specialized and sophisticated, demanding custom-designed solutions to accurately capture and analyze these high-frequency phenomena.

### Mechanical Oscillations

While the term "RF" is most commonly associated with electrical oscillations, it's important to acknowledge that mechanical systems can also operate at these high frequencies. Examples include [mechanical filters](/Mechanical_filter), which use resonant mechanical elements to select specific frequencies, and [RF MEMS](/RF_MEMS) (Micro-Electro-Mechanical Systems) devices that leverage mechanical principles for radio frequency applications.

